I study the information intermediation problem in the context of the following
 model.
 In the base setting, buyers are short-lived and care about rejection rates
 but do not care about who they match with.
 Sellers are long-lived, care less about matching rate but care about who
 they match with.
 Buyers contact sellers with a request of service.
 Sellers have limited capacity for serving buyers: if a seller accepts a
 job, he becomes busy for a period of time and cannot accept new jobs.
 The platform designs an information disclosure policy that governs what
 buyer information is available to sellers before they decide to accept
 or reject the buyer request.
 I consider the general platform's objective of maximizing the weighted
 average of buyer surplus and seller profits but for concreteness take welfare-m
aximization.
 
