 Given the buyer and seller preferences, to achieve efficiency the platform
 should achieve high match quality also making sure that the matches happen
 at a reasonable rate.
 However, match quality and match speed are in conflict.
 On the one hand, enforcing higher match rate requires sellers to accept
 more jobs.
 This degrades seller match quality because they need to accept more inferior
 jobs.
 As a result seller welfare decreases.
 On the other hand, letting sellers pick the most valuable buyers implies
 high rejection rates.
 High rejections rates decrease match speed and reduce buyer surplus.
 For example, on Uber, if drivers often reject passenger requests, passengers
 will have long wait times.
 On Airbnb, if hosts often reject guest inquiries, guests have to spend
 more time and effort searching.
 
